,"head(maxdly[order(maxdly$totalsteps, decreasing=TRUE),])"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","id":"6dbd5ba1","metadata":{"papermill":{"duration":0.008305,"end_time":"2023-10-05T13:40:32.249413","exception":false,"start_time":"2023-10-05T13:40:32.241108","status":"completed"},"tags":[]},"source":["That sums up the individual averages.\n","\n","### Analaysis - Part 1: Daily Activity\n","\n","By examining the average, it's easy to get a big picture idea of how often participants were moving every day. User 8877689391 walked the most steps on average with 16040 steps taken daily over the course of the two months from which the data was captured. As a whole, the 30 participants walked nearly 7638 steps each day. Based on this, it seems like each user was pretty active throughout the course of the day.\n","\n","But, the sedentary minutes give us a different picture. User 1927972279 was sedentary on average for 1317 minutes. As a group, the participants were sedentary for 991 minutes. This indicates that the FitBit users from this study are not very active throughout the day.\n","\n","\"Active minutes\" are not defined so it's hard to say what that means. But, when combining sedentary minutes and steps, it seems that users are probably getting steps in through typical daily activity (i.e. running errands) without necessarily exercising. Examining the hourly and intensity data can give better insight to this.\n","\n","# Methodology - Part 2\n","\n","The hourly information gives a more detailed snapshot than the daily data. It can help determine if my earlier conclusions were correct.\n","\n","## Hourly Average\n","\n","### Individual Average\n","\n","The methodology will follow largely the same pattern as it did with the daily data.\n","\n","First things first, I'll start by renaming the data and making all the column names lowercase."]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":6,"id":"6ea89de5","metadata":{"execution":{"iopub.execute_input":"2023-10-05T13:40:32.269456Z","iopub.statu